    "message_1": "Given the following table of values for a continuous function 𝑓(𝑥): \n\n𝑥 | -1 | 0 | 1 | 2\n--|---|---|---|--\n𝑓(𝑥) | 2 | 1 | 3 | 5\n\nFind the Lagrange polynomial that interpolates the data, and use it to approximate 𝑓(−0.5) and 𝑓(1.5).",
    "message_2": "To find the Lagrange polynomial that interpolates the data, we will use the Lagrange formula:\n\nL(x) = f(x0) * l0(x) + f(x1) * l1(x) + f(x2) * l2(x) + f(x3) * l3(x)\n\nwhere li(x) are the Lagrange basis polynomials:\n\nl0(x) = (x - x1)(x - x2)(x - x3) / [(x0 - x1)(x0 - x2)(x0 - x3)]\nl1(x) = (x - x0)(x - x2)(x - x3) / [(x1 - x0)(x1 - x2)(x1 - x3)]\nl2(x) = (x - x0)(x - x1)(x - x3) / [(x2 - x0)(x2 - x1)(x2 - x3)]\nl3(x) = (x - x0)(x - x1)(x - x2) / [(x3 - x0)(x3 - x1)(x3 - x2)]\n\nGiven the data points:\n\nx0 = -1, f(x0) = 2\nx1 = 0, f(x1) = 1\nx2 = 1, f(x2) = 3\nx3 = 2, f(x3) = 5\n\nWe can calculate the Lagrange basis polynomials:\n\nl0(x) = (x - 0)(x - 1)(x - 2) / [(-1 - 0)(-1 - 1)(-1 - 2)] = (x)(x - 1)(x - 2) / [(-1)(-2)(-3)] = -(x)(x - 1)(x - 2) / 6\nl1(x) = (x + 1)(x - 1)(x - 2) / [(0 + 1)(0 - 1)(0 - 2)] = (x + 1)(x - 1)(x - 2) / [(1)(-1)(-2)] = (x + 1)(x - 1)(x - 2) / 2\nl2(x) = (x + 1)(x)(x - 2) / [(1 + 1)(1)(1 - 2)] = (x + 1)(x)(x - 2) / [(2)(1)(-1)] = -(x + 1)(x)(x - 2) / 2\nl3(x) = (x + 1)(x)(x - 1) / [(2 + 1)(2)(2 - 1)] = (x + 1)(x)(x - 1) / [(3)(2)(1)] = (x + 1)(x)(x - 1) / 6\n\nNow we can find the Lagrange polynomial L(x):\n\nL(x) = 2 * l0(x) + 1 * l1(x) + 3 * l2(x) + 5 * l3(x)\nL(x) = -2(x)(x - 1)(x - 2) / 6 + (x + 1)(x - 1)(x - 2) / 2 - 3(x + 1)(x)(x - 2) / 2 + 5(x + 1)(x)(x - 1) / 6\n\nNow we can use L(x) to approximate f(-0.5) and f(1.5):\n\nL(-0.5) = -2(-0.5)(-0.5 - 1)(-0.5 - 2) / 6 + (-0.5 + 1)(-0.5 - 1)(-0.5 - 2) / 2 - 3(-0.5 + 1)(-0.5)(-0.5 - 2) / 2 + 5(-0.5 + 1)(-0.5)(-0.5 - 1) / 6\nL(-0.5) ≈ 1.25\n\nL(1.5) = -2(1.5)(1.5 - 1)(1.5 - 2) / 6 + (1.5 + 1)(1.5 - 1)(1.5 - 2) / 2 - 3(1.5 + 1)(1.5)(1.5 - 2) / 2 + 5(1.5 + 1)(1.5)(1.5 - 1) / 6\nL(1.5) ≈ 3.75\n\nSo, the approximations are f(-0.5) ≈ 1.25 and f(1.5) ≈ 3.75."
